1036→
1037→**How `SecondaryHunkStatus` is computed:**
1038→
1039→When the "unstaged diff" (working tree vs. index) has a secondary diff set
1040→to the "uncommitted diff" (working tree vs. HEAD), each hunk in the unstaged
1041→diff is compared against the uncommitted hunks:
1042→
1043→```rust
1044→fn compute_secondary_status(
1045→    unstaged_hunk: &DiffHunk,
1046→    uncommitted_hunks: &[DiffHunk],  // from the secondary diff
1047→) -> SecondaryHunkStatus {
1048→    // An uncommitted hunk covers the same buffer region:
1049→    let overlapping: Vec<_> = uncommitted_hunks
1050→        .iter()
1051→        .filter(|h| ranges_overlap(&h.buffer_range, &unstaged_hunk.buffer_range))
1052→        .collect();
1053→
1054→    if overlapping.is_empty() {
1055→        // No uncommitted hunk covers this range.
1056→        // This means the unstaged diff exists but the uncommitted diff does not
1057→        // → the change is in the index (staged) but not in HEAD → FULLY STAGED.
1058→        SecondaryHunkStatus::NoSecondaryHunk
1059→    } else if overlapping.iter().all(|h| h.buffer_range == unstaged_hunk.buffer_range) {
1060→        // Perfect match: both diffs have the same range.
1061→        // This means the change exists both as unstaged and in HEAD → FULLY UNSTAGED.
1062→        SecondaryHunkStatus::HasSecondaryHunk
1063→    } else {
1064→        // Partial overlap: some lines of this hunk are in HEAD, some are not.
1065→        SecondaryHunkStatus::OverlapsWithSecondaryHunk
1066→    }
1067→}
1068→```
1069→
1070→This is the mathematical heart of the "diff-of-diffs" algorithm. The
1071→insight is that comparing the *positions* of hunks in two separate diffs
1072→against HEAD naturally reveals which lines have been staged.
